shire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Shipbrook, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Shipbrook, Northwich, Cheshire, England":"Northwich, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud de Balliol was born in 1137, in Northamptonshire, England as the daughter of Reginald de Balliol. She married Warin de Vernon in 1154, in Shipbrook, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 6 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1173, in Shipbrook, Cheshire, England, at the age of 36."},"et":{"1137–1173":"1137–1173","1135–1190":"1135–1190","1154–1190":"1154–1190","1155–1195":"1155–1195","1155–1196":"1155–1196","1157–Male":"1157–Surnud","1165–1222":"1165–1222","1166–Male":"1166–Surnud","1170–1196":"1170–1196","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1154":"1154","1165":"1165","1120":"1120","1196":"1196","1173":"1173","1195":"1195","1170":"1170","1137":"1137","1157":"1157","1135":"1135","1222":"1222","1155":"1155","1166":"1166","about 1157":"umbes 1157","after 1166":"pärast 1166","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Shipbrook, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, England","England":"England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Shipbrook, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shipbrook, Northwich, Cheshire, England":"Northwich, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1137–1173":"1137–1173","1135–1190":"1135–1190","1154–1190":"1154–1190","1155–1195":"1155–1195","1155–1196":"1155–1196","1157–Male":"1157–Kuollut","1165–1222":"1165–1222","1166–Male":"1166–Kuollut","1170–1196":"1170–1196","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1120–Male":"1120–Kuollut","1190":"1190","about 1170":"noin 1170","1154":"1154","1165":"1165","1120":"1120","1196":"1196","1173":"1173","1195":"1195","1170":"1170","1137":"1137","1157":"1157","1135":"1135","1222":"1222","1155":"1155","1166":"1166","about 1157":"noin 1157","after 1166":"1166 jälkeen","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Shipbrook, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, England","England"